---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CaseHero from '../../components/CaseHero.astro';
import CasePrevNext from '../../components/CasePrevNext.astro';
import CTABanner from '../../components/CTABanner.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Beat Saber — Beat Games" description="3 global VR launches. One scalable visual system that honored Britney, Metallica, and Monstercat without losing a single pixel of Beat Saber's DNA." ogImage="/images/beat_saber_hero.webp" ogType="article">
  <CaseHero logo="/images/beat_saber_logo.webp" logoAlt="Beat Saber / Beat Games" title="Beat Saber — Beat Games" category="Creative Systems & Brand Strategy" meta={[{label:'Client',value:'Beat Games / Meta Reality Labs'},{label:'Role',value:'Senior UX Strategist'},{label:'Scope',value:'Multi-phase — 3 artist pack releases'},{label:'Deliverables',value:'3D environments, key art, in-game visuals, brand architecture'}]} heroImage="/images/beat_saber_hero.webp" heroAlt="Beat Saber VR environment — neon visual design" />
  <div class="case-body">
    <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/beat_saber_intro.webp" alt="Beat Saber brand architecture overview" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">The Problem</h2>
      <p>Each Beat Saber Music Pack launch is a product release and a cultural event simultaneously. The game had 4 million active players at the time of this engagement. Each artist pack introduced a globally recognized name. The design challenge was real: honor what each artist's audience already associated with them visually, without losing what made Beat Saber's identity coherent across three very different music genres.</p>
      <p>Co-branding in a VR environment is harder than it sounds. The environments aren't decoration. They're functional: players need spatial depth cues for note timing, visual contrast between sabers and background, and consistent lighting that doesn't create motion discomfort.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Research & Discovery</h2>
      <p>I reviewed documented player feedback from three prior Music Pack launches to understand which environmental decisions correlated with positive play experience versus complaints. The consistent success factors: strong spatial contrast between note objects and background surfaces, lighting that moved in sync with musical tempo rather than independently, and environmental storytelling that communicated genre before the first note was hit.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Brand Architecture Framework</h2>
      <p>I developed a flexible visual system organized around three dimensions: Artist Authenticity, Beat Saber DNA, and Gameplay Readability. The system established what was fixed across all packs — the red/blue saber color system, note contrast requirements, and spatial depth standards — and what was variable: artist-specific palettes, materials, environmental narrative, and lighting choreography.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Britney Spears Music Pack</h2>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Pop Nostalgia Meets Neon Euphoria</h6>
      <div class="case-grid-2">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_britney01.webp" alt="Britney Spears pack — hero environment" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_britney02.webp" alt="Britney Spears pack — neon heart element" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
      </div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Visual Strategy</h6>
      <ul class="case-bullets">
        <li><strong>Hero Element:</strong> A luminous 3D heart — both literal in representing emotion and metaphorical as the 'heart' of the Beat Saber experience.</li>
        <li><strong>Color Psychology:</strong> Magenta-to-blue gradients evoke nightclub energy and emotional resonance.</li>
        <li><strong>Typography Treatment:</strong> Neon signage aesthetic that is energetic yet elegant, bridging 2000s club culture with contemporary design.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="case-grid-3">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_britney03.webp" alt="Britney pack — color palette" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_britney04.webp" alt="Britney pack — environment lighting" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_britney05.webp" alt="Britney pack — spatial design" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
      </div>
      <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/beat_saber_britney06.webp" alt="Britney Spears pack — full environment render" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">User Experience Impact</h6>
      <p>The radiant, euphoric environment enhances the emotional accessibility of Britney's music while preserving gameplay clarity. Players described feeling 'inside the music' rather than simply playing to it.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Monstercat Mixtape Vol. 2</h2>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Futuristic Bass-Driven Atmosphere</h6>
      <div class="case-grid-2">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_monster01.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — mascot sculpture" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_monster02.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — laser corridor" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
      </div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Strategic Insight</h6>
      <p>Monstercat embodies genre fluidity in electronic music, with a brand that thrives on evolution and cross-genre experimentation. Its visual identity must feel kinetic, innovative, and always in motion.</p>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Visual Strategy</h6>
      <ul class="case-bullets">
        <li><strong>Hero Element:</strong> The Monstercat mascot is reimagined as a high-gloss metallic sculpture, transforming the 2D logo into a dimensional brand presence.</li>
        <li><strong>Environmental Design:</strong> A high-energy corridor features reactive columns and volumetric laser beams, creating a sense of sonic architecture.</li>
        <li><strong>Lighting System:</strong> Dynamic beams mirror the rhythm of gameplay, producing visual echoes of bass drops and transitions.</li>
        <li><strong>Material Palette:</strong> Deep violets, bright reds, and icy blues emphasize energy shifts and genre transitions.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="case-grid-3">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_monster03.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — material palette" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_monster04.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — corridor detail" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_monster05.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — lighting system" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
      </div>
      <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/beat_saber_monster06.webp" alt="Monstercat pack — full environment render" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">User Experience Impact</h6>
      <p>The environment serves as a responsive performance space. Metallic surfaces and a laser grid provide depth cues that enhance spatial awareness in VR, visually expressing Monstercat's brand philosophy: sound as structure, rhythm as architecture.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Metallica Music Pack</h2>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Power, Distortion, and Thunder</h6>
      <div class="case-grid-2">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica01.webp" alt="Metallica pack — industrial storm field" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica02.webp" alt="Metallica pack — metallic cube grid" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
      </div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Strategic Insight</h6>
      <p>Metallica introduces its established audience to VR gaming. The primary design challenge was to translate the band's raw, analog energy — distorted guitars and thunderous drums — into Beat Saber's clean, digital visual style while preserving both brands' identities.</p>
      <h6 class="case-h6">Visual Strategy</h6>
      <ul class="case-bullets">
        <li><strong>Hero Element:</strong> A grid of metallic cubes represents rhythm blocks, each charged with a blue energy core.</li>
        <li><strong>Environmental Design:</strong> An industrial storm field where electricity is visible, tangible, and rhythmic.</li>
        <li><strong>Material Development:</strong> Brushed steel shaders feature emissive blue surfaces, with each reflection pulsing with energy.</li>
        <li><strong>Brand Integration:</strong> Metallica's lightning bolt logo is unified with Beat Saber's red and blue mark, establishing a co-branded visual language.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="case-grid-3">
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica03.webp" alt="Metallica pack — steel material detail" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica04.webp" alt="Metallica pack — lightning arc" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
        <img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica05.webp" alt="Metallica pack — brand mark integration" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="500" height="360" />
      </div>
      <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/beat_saber_metallica06.webp" alt="Metallica pack — full environment render" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
      <h6 class="case-h6">User Experience Impact</h6>
      <p>The environment translates aggressive sonic energy into a spatial experience. Lightning arcs offer directional cues, while metallic surfaces convey weight and impact. Players reported feeling the music's physicality more intensely — a critical success metric for rhythm-based VR experiences.</p>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section case-section--results">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Results & Impact</h2>
      <ul class="case-results">
        <li><strong>Player reach:</strong> 4M+ active players at time of engagement across all three pack launches</li>
        <li><strong>Launch execution:</strong> 3 global simultaneous launches with full asset delivery across all platforms, zero timeline slips</li>
        <li><strong>Player feedback:</strong> Britney pack — 'inside the music' cited in post-launch community feedback threads</li>
        <li><strong>Brand framework:</strong> Visual system adopted as reusable architecture for subsequent Music Pack releases</li>
        <li><strong>Asset library:</strong> Scalable component library delivered for future pack development without starting from scratch</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">My Contribution</h2>
      <p>I owned the brand architecture framework and the visual design of all three environments. 3D modeling and rendering execution was handled by the technical team at Beat Games, working from my design direction, reference materials, and asset specifications. The co-branding decisions — particularly the Metallica mark unification — involved alignment across multiple brand teams; my role was to make the design case for a solution that worked for everyone rather than defaulting to compromise.</p>
      <p>If I were revisiting this work, I'd push for in-headset prototype testing earlier in the process. Reviewing 3D environment designs on a 2D screen consistently understates the spatial experience, and there were a few lighting decisions that read differently in VR than they did in the reference renders.</p>
    </section>
  </div>
  <CasePrevNext currentSlug="beat-saber" />
  <CTABanner />
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
